r:id>AD470017-8514-4B7F-B163-7D47C0A74586</gtr:id><gtr:sector>Charity/Non Profit</gtr:sector><gtr:start>2016-01-01</gtr:start></gtr:furtherFundingOutput></gtr:furtherFundingOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs><gtr:policyInfluenceOutput><gtr:areas/><gtr:description>Evaluation of Health Extension Program</gtr:description><gtr:geographicReach>National</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>D610653A-2904-468B-8802-C3E2D8700031</gtr:id><gtr:type>Participation in a national consultation</gtr:type></gtr:policyInfluenceOutput></gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs><gtr:productOutputs><gtr:productOutput><gtr:description>The public health intervention under development is a primary health care strategy for pastoral community, which is the main objective of the research project. It is at its early stage, where different sources of information are being reviewed and key issues are under discussion. The principal source of funding is the Medical Research Council.</gtr:description><gtr:id>39CDAEF1-AC94-4F97-A65F-9FE65C81D791</gtr:id><gtr:impact>It is under refinement stage. It is not yet implemented and hence there is no impact from its actual implementation yet, but its indication on the need for new approach has created behavioral change on key stakeholders, particularly on the implementers and policy makers.</gtr:impact><gtr:stage>Refinement.  Non-clinical</gtr:stage><gtr:status>Under active development/distribution</gtr:status><gtr:title>Public health intervention design</gtr:title><gtr:type>Health and Social Care Services</gtr:type><gtr:yearDevCompleted>2017</gtr:yearDevCompleted></gtr:productOutput><gtr:productOutput><gtr:description>The intervention is called Health Development Army (HDA). It is a broad-based community mobilization platform, which involves grouping 20-30 households who reside in the same sub-locality into development teams, and then, each team is organized into one-to-five networks of six households living in the same neighborhood. The members of the networks are women. This intervention approach was conceived as a result of the MRC funded project. During the initiation stage of our project, our research team was involved in stakeholder engagement activities to create awareness of the objectives and methodology of the research project. During these multiple discussions with various key stakeholders in Borena zone, in addition to the inappropriateness of the existing Health Extension Program for pastoral context, another key challenge voiced by many was lack of community mobilization and participation affecting the pastoral health system. To address this challenge and strengthen community mobilization and ownership, we designed networks of women development army based on a similar approach designed for agrarian communities in Ethiopia. This community engagement approach is being subjected to formative evaluation through funding secured from the International Initiative for Impact Evaluation (3ie). The 3ie funding (PI: Hailay Desta Teklehaimanot) started in January 2016. At this stage, women have been organized into development teams and one-to-five networks. The leaders of the development teams and one-to-five networks have received training and equipped with the necessary knowledge and skills to enable them influence their respective members on promotive and preventive health services. Draft intervention strategy has been developed, which will be followed by a series of evaluations and revisions to come up with the best community engagement approach for pastoral context. The health impact of the intervention approach will evaluated through the measurement of pre- and post-intervention immunization coverage. The pre-intervention household survey has already been undertaken prior the implementation of the intervention.</gtr:description><gtr:id>605C9A95-AB7C-41B8-81D8-CF0B997F0F27</gtr:id><gtr:impact>While the intervention is being subjected to formative evaluation and before the project is completed, the Zonal Health Department and Zonal Women Affairs have started to implement the intervention in all villages of the zone.</gtr:impact><gtr:stage>Initial development</gtr:stage><gtr:status>Under active development/distribution</gtr:status><gtr:title>Community engagement</gtr:title><gtr:type>Health and Social Care Services</gtr:type><gtr:yearDevCompleted>2016</gtr:yearDevCompleted></gtr:productOutput></gtr:productOutputs><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications/><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">MR/M006050/1</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories><gtr:healthCategory><gtr:id>F3822669-BB5A-4BB4-BAE0-DCB9DE36E092</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>100</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Generic Health Relevance</gtr:text></gtr:healthCategory></gtr:healthCategories><gtr:researchActivities><gtr:researchActivity><gtr:id>E4AF608A-CDB6-4CE6-AA10-95B3E043E22F</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>100</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>8.1  Organisation and delivery of services</gtr:text></gtr:researchActivity></gtr:researchActivities><gtr:researchSubjects/><gtr:researchTopics/><gtr:rcukProgrammes><gtr:rcukProgramme><gtr:id>D640D1B8-B141-4DFC-BCD3-CEADD848A918</gtr:id><gtr:text>GCRF</gtr:text></gtr:rcukProgramme></gtr:rcukProgrammes></gtr:project></gtr:projectComposition></gtr:projectOverview>